programme.desc: 10/20/82: With the championship on the line, Bruce Sutter comes into the game in the 8th inning to blank the Brewers. The Cardinals captured their ninth World Series win in a dramatic Game 7 win at Busch Stadium.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/10/1982 - Cecil Cooper plates a pair of runs on a go-ahead single in the bottom 7th inning and the Brewers hold on to secure a 4-3 win over the Angels, punching their ticket to the 1982 World Series.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/14/84: Kirk Gibson clinched the Tigers' 1984 World Series win with a three-run homer off Goose Gossage. With the win, Sparky Anderson becomes the first manager ever to win a championship in both the American and National Leagues.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/14/85 - Heading into Game 5 of the 1985 NLCS, Ozzie Smith had just 13 career home runs and none of them were from the left side of the plate. That's why when he walked if off against the Dodgers with a homer to right field, the fans went crazy.
programme.sub-title: Ozzie Smith hits unlikely walk-off homer

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/27/86: In the 500th World Series Game, the Red Sox and Mets battled it out in Game 7 at Shea Stadium. The Mets scored two insurance runs in the 8th inning. The franchise took home their second championship, defeating Boston, 8-5.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/15/86: The Astros scored three runs in the 1st inning and took the lead deep into the 9th, until the Mets retaliated with three runs to send the game into extras.
programme.sub-title: 10/15/86: Mets win NLCS thriller in 16 innings

programme.title: World's Greatest: Island Arks
programme.desc: Cut off from continents, remote islands have become floating arks, attracting migrating species and forging new ones. Take a privileged glimpse into the secret lives of the rare and exotic species that inhabit these lost worlds.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Sacred Sites
programme.desc: Ancient in architecture and detailed in design, these man-made masterpieces stand as testaments to the strength of human faith. These sites endure as a timeless reminder of resilience, respect, and the need to reflect.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Water Adventures
programme.desc: We are captivated by oceans, rivers, and lakes - the power, the flow, the reflective stillness. And as we seek to get closer, we immerse ourselves in an expanding range of aquatic experiences.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coasts
programme.desc: Along coasts, one element ends and another begins. No two days are ever the same on a coastline: the only thing that remains a constant is the timeless power of the sea.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Forest Animals
programme.desc: Forest Animals gets up close with bears, koalas, moose, wolves, weaver ants, and Tasmanian Devils. This episode roves dark forests floors and soars above vast canopies of green in America, China, Laos, and Australia.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coral Islands
programme.desc: The reef systems that gave rise to coral islands support the vast majority of marine species on our planet, but they are under threat. Explore the delicate balance between exploiting and preserving these extraordinary natural wonders.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Wetland Animals
programme.desc: Wetland Animals dives into the swamps, rivers, and flood plains of the Everglades, Botswana’s Okavango Delta, Kakadu National Park in Australia, and the Amazon to see deadly crocodiles, piranhas, hippopotamus, flamingo, manatee, and platypus.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Flights
programme.desc: Our experience of the world’s greatest marvels is literally and figuratively elevated when we explore them from the air. Whether you travel by air balloon, helicopter, light aircraft, a grand perspective is always guaranteed.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Bridges
programme.desc: A bridge is a structure that’s designed to transcend, but a great bridge can define the place where it stands. Symbols of human ingenuity, beauty, and grandeur, bridges connect us not only to each other but also to the past.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Global Cities
programme.desc: Travel to the centers of wealth, power, industry, and innovation. From London to Tokyo, Hong Kong to New York, these are the cities that never sleep. The influence held in these economic hubs unites the global community.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Drives
programme.desc: A journey by road expands our horizons, allowing us to explore the depth and breadth of whole countries and continents, stopping whenever and wherever we chose.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanic Islands
programme.desc: They've been worshiped and feared over the millennia. But in the wake of drama and destruction, the elements give rise to cultures and nations so beautiful that we've come to know them as the world's greatest volcanic islands.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Iconic Buildings
programme.desc: In construction, only a few buildings can be groundbreaking. Vastly different in shape, size, and function, these diverse buildings prove there is no recipe for greatness, just the fundamental ingredients of vision, bravery, and imagination.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Treks
programme.desc: Every journey made by foot promises a grand adventure. From the highest mountains to the wildest jungle realms, treks venture down the road less travelled, allowing us to connect to nature, history, and culture, one step at a time.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Port Cities
programme.desc: Some of the most stunning cities are port cities - Sydney, Rio, Cape Town - and are also some of the most culturally diverse and vibrant. The great maritime cities of the world bridge countries and continents and unite the global community.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Glaciers
programme.desc: Clinging to the world’s highest mountains and forming ice caps on both poles, glaciers leave an impression on the landscape and on all who bear witness to their splendor.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Ancient Cities
programme.desc: In Ancient Cities, we journey to these ancestors of influence such as Luang Prabang, Vienna, and Istanbul where religious and cultural centers have shaped the ways in which we view the world around us and continue to do so in modern times.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Marine Animals
programme.desc: From the surprises of colorful reef characters to effervescent penguins, killer sharks, and regal whales, dive into the places where nature reveals itself in some of its most marvelous and bizarre forms.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Through history, armies marched to face each other on favored ground and clashed to decide a campaign, a war, an empire. With the 20th century that changed. The battles of the WWII happened anywhere and everywhere, in every weather and climate.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Some words transcend their origins as humble place names. They are carved into history as turning points which influenced the course of WWII, the fate of nations, and the make-up of our world. El Alameine, Okinawa, and Pearl Harbor.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Aristocrat and the Balkan Communists
programme.desc: Fitzroy Maclean, an MP and WWII spy, supported Tito's Communist partisans in Yugoslavia against the Germans, forging a lasting friendship and honored at Tito's funeral post-war.
programme.sub-title: The Aristocrat and the Balkan Communists

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Agent Garbo
programme.desc: Juan Pujol, MI6's WWII agent "Garbo," created a fictitious spy network in Lisbon, deceiving the Germans with crucial disinformation and influencing their strategies. After the war, MI6 protected him, and he lived in Venezuela until his death in 1988.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Christine Granville
programme.desc: Christine Granville, aka Krystyna Skarbek, a brave SOE agent, secured the release of captured comrades from the Gestapo before Operation Dragoon, earning the George Medal.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The French Triple Agent
programme.desc: Operation Cockade, led by MI6's double agent Henri Dericourt in 1943, aimed to deceive Germans with sabotage. Despite efforts, Germans withdrew divisions unconvinced. Dericourt faced a post-war treason trial and died in a mysterious 1962 plane crash.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Spymistress and the French Fiasco
programme.desc: After WWII, SOE disbanded, leaving Vera Atkins to uncover fates of 118 agents, including 13 women. Many were betrayed and sent to camps; some were executed. Atkins' quest continued, marked by personal impact and delayed recognition.
programme.sub-title: The Spymistress and the French Fiasco

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The SAS Italian Job
programme.desc: In 1945, during the Italian Spring offensive, SOE agent Michael Lees and SAS officer Roy Farran led a raid on German HQs at Villa Rossi and Villa Calvi. Despite orders to cancel, Farran attacked with SAS men and partisans, killing many Germans.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Dutch Disaster
programme.desc: Operation North Pole was a WWII German deception using captured SOE agents to mislead Britain. 47 of 50 agents were captured. Despite warnings, SOE ignored signs of compromise to maintain support, leading to a major intelligence failure.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Scholar and the Fight for Greece
programme.desc: Monty Woodhouse, a professor and a legend for blowing up the Gorgopotamos Bridge in Greece in 1942. In the British counter attack against Rommell at Al Alamein in North Africa it was vital to disrupt German supply routes, Greece.
programme.sub-title: The Scholar and the Fight for Greece

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Banker, the Norwegians & the Bomb
programme.desc: Sir Charles attended Eton, and then joined the Coldstream Guards. He won the Military Cross on the Western Front and, having survived the war, returned to banking.
programme.sub-title: The Banker, the Norwegians & the Bomb

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Double Agent Tricycle
programme.desc: Dusan Popov was almost certainly James Bond. Ian Fleming knew all the stories about him. Popov managed to persuade both the Germans and MI6 to keep him in the style of a millionaire businessman while performing a series of missions against the Nazis.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Mafia Connection
programme.desc: Lucky Luciano, a mafia boss of the 1930s, was in jail in 1942 on charges of running prostitution rings. US intelligence services did a deal with him and he got the Italians to share intelligence on German U boat movements.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Hardy Amies and Operation Ratweek
programme.desc: Operation Ratweek’s existence has always been denied. However WMR has now discovered evidence that it existed and was carried out.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Special Interrogation Group
programme.desc: The SIG consisted of German speaking Jewish volunteers from Palestine. They had a highly dangerous job: which was to pose as Germans behind enemy lines and extract intelligence and do acts of sabotage. Few had a long-life expectancy.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: In this programme we bring the RAF story into the modern era. Another aircraft to have extended the RAF’s capabilities is the C130 Hercules. This aircraft has proved its capabilities in countless environments from resupply, to dropping paratroopers.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: The RAF’s maritime role is often overlooked. Between the wars the RAF operated elegant flying boats to patrol the far flung corners of the Empire.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: X-Rated
programme.desc: Adolf Hitler had a depraved sex life that he tried to keep hidden from the German public. He was said to be a chronic masturbator, a voyeur and that he engaged in sado-masochistic sex with women.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Body Image
programme.desc: Hitler wanted the world to believe he possessed super-human qualities but in private he was a wreck. This episode reveals the archives that confirm Hitler’s genital deformity, the alarming truth about his heavy drug addiction and the Parkinson’s.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Family Matters
programme.desc: Adolf Hitler's father was a violent, abusive man. His mother doted on her young son. This episode delves deep into the psychology of Hitler as the narcissistic child who grew into a malignant psychopath full of rage and deep hatred.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Suicidal Maidens
programme.desc: Using extensive archival research, this program explores the squalid secrets he lied and killed to protect

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Genocide 1942-1944
programme.desc: Genocide 1942 - 1944: Along with Treblinka and Majdanek, Sobibor was one of the camps used in Operation Reinhard, in which the Nazis murdered almost two million people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Armageddon 1943-1945
programme.desc: Armageddon 1943-1945: The defeat at Stalingrad in 1943 was the turning point of the war and convinced the Nazi leadership to intensify their terror and propaganda campaigns.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: From The "Protection Squadron" To The SS State.
programme.desc: From the Protection Squadron to the SS State: Trace the rise to power of the SS as we examine several perpetrators. Who was recruited? And why was the SS attractive to men?
programme.sub-title: From The "Protection Squadron" To The SS State.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: Heinrich Himmler
programme.desc: Heinrich Himmler: An agriculturalist by trade, he went on to lead the SS and tried to escape responsibility at the end of the war. Who was Heinrich Himmler?

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: The Executioner: Reinhard Heydrich
programme.desc: The Executioner: Reinhard Heydrich: More than any other Nazi leader, Heydrich was an orchestrator of mass murder, and was terrifyingly clinical in approach.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: The Waffen-SS
programme.desc: The Waffen-SS: Masqueraded as military excellence, the reality was very different. Recruits were poorly trained and remorse was nonexistent, as SS troops killed mercilessly.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: The SS Death Head's Unit
programme.desc: The SS Death Head's Unit: Tasked with guarding concentration camps, this unit's actions knew no bounds, and, despite their heinous acts, still attended social gatherings.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: Unrepentant: The SS And Its Myth After 1945
programme.desc: Unrepentant: The SS and Its Myth After 1945: Drawing a line to the present, the atrocities of the SS are beyond all doubt, yet, there is a cult surrounding 'old comrades' today.
programme.sub-title: Unrepentant: The SS And Its Myth After 1945

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: Rise of The Bomber
programme.desc: Rise of the Bomber: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain as the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: War Without Boundaries
programme.desc: War Without Boundaries: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain as the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: The Means To Victory
programme.desc: The Means to Victory: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain as the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: The World At War
programme.desc: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain, and the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: By Night & By Day
programme.desc: By Night & By Day: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain, and the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Seeds of Violence 1918-1922
programme.desc: The Seeds of Violence 1918-1922: In the wake of the First World War, Adolf Hitler identifies Benito Mussolini as his model and has one ultimate goal: to gain power in Germany.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928
programme.desc: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928: Hitler appears to be eliminated after his failed putsch in 1923. Discover how the Nazi movement used democracy's tolerance in Germany to come back.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Democracy without Democrats 1929-1933
programme.desc: Democracy Without Democrats 1929-1933: A protest turns into a racist and anti-Jewish movement during the 1920s and the NSDAP use emotions to gain the loyalty of the people.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: An old-time candy bar; mountains of cannelloni; Vietnamese rice noodles; diced butternut squash.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: Maple syrup; Almond Roca butter toffee popcorn; Turkish delight; apples that taste like grapes.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: Fruit leather; cheese curds; Hello Dolly bars; Canadian-made guacamole.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: Handmade exotic truffles; eco-friendly coffee pods; vegetable dumplings; Moon Cheese.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: Caviar worth 12 thousand a bowl; shepherd's pie; risotto balls; ice wine truffles.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: A legendary sandwich snack; frozen fruit bars from Florida; blueberry perogies; mountain of kale chips.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: Melt-in-your-mouth mint chocolates; asparagus antipasto; Aussie-style licorice; plantain chips.

programme.title: Food Factory
programme.desc: Peanut butter cups with a butterscotch twist; mountains of pound cake; triple citrus jelly; butter chicken cooking sauce.

programme.title: The Secret Order
programme.desc: Phil Comeau shines a spotlight on the Ordre de Jacques-Cartier and paints a gripping portrait of the social and political struggles of Canadian francophone-minority communities.

programme.title: Canada Vignettes Log Drivers Waltz
programme.desc: A young girl who loves to dance and is ready to marry chooses a log driver over his more well-to-do, land-loving competition. Driving logs down the river has made him the best dancing partner to be found.

programme.title: The Man Who Stole Dreams
programme.desc: This enchanting and magical animation film, an ode to our dreams during the night, celebrates the creative imagination, uniqueness, and the human spirit. The plot involves a man who steals the dreams of villagers, the tries to sell them back to the them.

programme.title: Tu As Crie Let Me Go
programme.desc: In "Tu as crié LET ME GO," Anne Claire Poirier explores her daughter's tragic descent into drugs and prostitution, seeking understanding of the societal pressures influencing young people's risky behaviors in Montreal's streets.

programme.title: Best Time Of My Life Portraits Of Women In Mid-Life, The
programme.desc: An upbeat, positive film about a group of women dealing with mid-life and menopause. The women come from a wide range of backgrounds, careers and lifestyles, it effectively dispels popular myths and fears about life during and after menopause.

programme.title: Gurdeep Singh Bains
programme.desc: Gurdeep is a thirteen-year-old Canadian Sikh whose family runs a dairy farm near Chilliwack, British Columbia. They have retained their language and religion. Sometimes he feels a little different from the other children because he wears a turban.

programme.title: Le Grand Serpent Du Monde
programme.desc: A young forty-something, Tom Paradise refuses to grow up. Behind the wheel of his bus he drives endlessly through the city, tracing out the path of his life, dreaming of the landscape of the American West that forever impressed him

programme.title: Challenger An Industrial Romance
programme.desc: Follows the development of Canadair's super-executive jet. The film captures the spirit of the Canadian air transport industry and its attempt to compete with the American leaders in the industry.

programme.title: Waiting
programme.desc: The patient Dinkas of South Sudan endure famine amid civil strife. Aid arrives in Alek, but distribution is delayed to prevent unrest, revealing the stark reality of hunger.

programme.title: Benoit
programme.desc: Benoît is an astonishingly accomplished eleven-year-old Québécois from Joliette. He pursues such diverse activities as weight lifting and playing the violin.

programme.title: Very Nice Very Nice
programme.desc: Arthur Lipsett's debut film peels back life's facade, revealing hidden anxieties beneath. Through familiar images and fragmented speech, it critiques societal norms, punctuated by the recurring phrase, "Very nice, very nice.

programme.title: Ill Find A Way
programme.desc: When nine-year-old Nadia is allowed to attend a regular school, she knows the kids will tease her but she'll "find a way to deal with it." Nadia has spina bifida, a congenital condition that has caused a lack of sensation from the knees down.

programme.title: Mother Earth/La Terre Notre Mere
programme.desc: Mother Earth is a short, evocative, poetic film that celebrates life on our planet. This documentary film looks at the reality of human beings; the earth is our home and we are profoundly connected to all other beings.

programme.title: Sea Dream
programme.desc: Children, like adults, have days that go wrong. This film shows how one little girl overcomes the day's frustrations by diving into an underwater fantasy where she spends time with her friend, the lady octopus.

programme.title: Danish Poet, The
programme.desc: Can we trace the chain of events that leads to our own birth? Is our existence just coincidence? The Danish Poet considers these questions as we follow a poet whose creative well has run dry, on a holiday to Norway to meet a famous writer.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Wings On Her Shoulder
programme.desc: This is a 1943 recruitment film. Although it specifically promises women jobs in post-war aviation, its primary message is that women fulfill support positions "so that men might fly.

programme.title: King Of The Hill
programme.desc: Spring 1972. The Chicago Cubs are poised to win the National League's Pennant race, lead by their star pitcher, a Black Canadian named Ferguson Jenkins, who was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1991. This is his story.

programme.title: Writer In The Nuclear Age A Conversation With Margaret Laurence
programme.desc: Margaret Laurence tackles peace-related issues in this short film: writer's social responsibility, language's impact, nuclear threat, and more. Ideal for sparking discussions across various subjects.

programme.title: Sylvies Story
programme.desc: The film shows Sylvie in a Montréal transition house, highlighting the hurdles of violence, loneliness, and scarcity. It emphasizes sharing experiences and transition houses' support in connecting victims with legal and social aid.

programme.title: Long Time Comin
programme.desc: There is a cultural revolution going on in Canada and Faith Nolan and Grace Channer are on the leading edge. These two African-Canadian lesbian artists give back to art its most urgent meanings--commitment and passion.

programme.title: In Full Voice
programme.desc: Muslim women are disconcerting, intriguing, polarizing—and straitjacketed by conflations of ideas in front-page stories. The film sits down with six Muslim Canadian women eager to talk about what shapes their identities.

programme.title: Christophers Movie Matinee
programme.desc: When movie cameras were put in the hands of a few young people, they made this film about themselves and their world. The film is revealing in what it shows of a dissenting generation and its rationale.

programme.title: The Tender Tale Of Cinderella Penguin
programme.desc: Medieval-style animation twists Cinderella with a mistreated penguin. Hilarity ensues when she loses her magic flipper, saved by Prince Charming. A wordless film with a unique fairy tale twist.

programme.title: Men of the Deeps
programme.desc: Men of the Deeps is a moving portrait of a group of former Cape Breton miners gathered together by their love of song. They are all members of the Men of the Deeps chorus, whose performances of traditional and contemporary songs evoke their working lives

programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Ägypten
programme.desc: Ägypten bedeutet Pharaonen, Pyramiden und vor allem – Wüste. In der feindlichen Umgebung leben alle Arten von Tieren. Die alten Ägypter glaubten, dass diese Kreaturen die Natur, Mond, Tag und Nacht kontrollieren.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Das Meer verwandelt sich zusehends. Die azurblaue See von Durban unterscheidet sich grundlegend von der rauen Meeresküste des Kaps. Gemeinsam mit dem österreichischen Haiforscher Dietmar Posch startet Andreas auf eine Expedition in die warmen Gewässer vor der Küste

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Nigel Marvens wilde Philippinen
programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Marokkos weißes Gold
programme.desc: Die Arganie, ein dornenbewehrter Baum, wächst nur im Südwesten Marokkos. Seine Früchte liefern das begehrte Arganöl, welches von den Frauen der Region seit Jahrhunderten in mühevoller Handarbeit produziert wird. Inzwischen kommen auch Europäer auf den Geschmack dieser einzigartigen Kostbarkeit. Und nicht nur das: Neben seinen kulinarischen Qualitäten lässt sich das Öl ebenso gut als Kosmetikprodukt und Heilmittel vermarkten. Planet Weltweit hat den Frauen Marokkos bei der aufwändigen Ölherstellung über die Schulter geschaut und beobachtet, wie sie sie versuchen, ihr traditionelles Kleinod für den internationalen Wettbewerb vorzubereiten.Sechs Uhr morgens in einem kleinen Dorf im Südwesten Marokkos. Die Männer sind bereits zur Arbeit aufgebrochen. Auch Arbia el Kasri verlässt das Haus, um ihrem Beruf nachzugehen. Vor fünf Jahren noch war es für eine Frau unvorstellbar außerhalb des Hauses Arbeit zu finden. In dieser Region Marokkos verlassen die Bäuerinnen eigentlich nie ihre Douar, ihre kleinen Dörfer. Doch nun sind es einige Hunderte, die sich wie Arbia täglich in kleinen Kooperativen einfinden, welche die Frauen selbst gegründet haben. Hier produzieren sie Arganöl - eine Kunst, die Marokkanerinnen bereits seit Jahrhunderten beherrschen. Das Öl ist überaus nährstoffre ...

programme.title: Der Weinpriester von Bali
programme.desc: Bali - Tropenparadies und Insel der Götter. Dem 42-jährigen Hindu Rai Budarsa gelang es als Erstem, Wein auf Bali zu kultivieren. Dreimal im Jahr kann auf der tropischen Insel geerntet werden. Für den Unternehmer ein Segen - doch für den gläubigen Hindu in Anbetracht der vielen religiösen Feste und Zeremonien eine Herausforderung. Ob Rai Budarsa der Balanceakt zwischen dem harten Alltag eines Unternehmers und seinen religiösen Verpflichtungen gelingt, davon erzählt diese Episode von Planet Weltweit.Bereits seit einer Stunde wartet die Prozession für die Leichenbestattung auf der Straße. Rai Budarsa streift eilig sein Poloshirt und die Bermudas ab, denn als höchster Vertreter einer Priesterkaste muss er jede Zeremonie in seiner Gemeinde leiten. Als sein Blackberry klingelt, schafft er es gerade noch den Knoten seines schwarzen Sarongs festzuziehen, bevor er den Anruf entgegennimmt. Es ist sein Kellermeister, der Australier Don Buchanan: Ihm fehlen Flaschen für die Abfüllung des Pino de Bali, dem Spitzenprodukt seines Unternehmens Hatten Wines. Der Container mit den Flaschen hängt irgendwo fest - ausgerechnet jetzt, wo während der religiösen Feiertage auf Bali die Restaurants und Hotels mit dem regionalen Wein beliefert werden müssen. Im Laufschritt verspricht Rai Budar ...

programme.title: Die Köchin von Bahia
programme.desc: Die afro-brasilianische Kultur ist nirgendwo so lebendig wie in Salvador de Bahia und in der Religion Candombl?. Die Köchin Elaine Cruz lebt und kocht nach den Regeln dieser Religion und zaubert einzigartige Spezialitäten, die Götter und Menschen gleichermaßen munden. Planet Weltweit hat Elaine beim Kochen für ein großes Fest einer Candombl?-Gemeinde über die Schulter geschaut.

programme.title: Freiheit auf Pferderücken
programme.sub-title: Der lange Weg der Nez Perce
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: 1877 weigerten sich rund 750 Angehörige des Stammes der Nez Perce, im Nordwesten der USA, ihre Freiheit aufzugeben und sich in ein Reservat zu begeben. Stattdessen begaben sie sich mit 2.000 Pferden, überwiegend Appaloosas, auf eine abenteuerliche und verlustreiche Flucht über gut 2.000 km quer durch die Rocky Mountains.

programme.title: Laos
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Wasserbüffel gelten in Laos als "Sparbücher für Notzeiten". Muss jemand ins Krankenhaus, geht der Reis aus oder steht eine Hochzeit an, verkauft man einen Büffel. Doch die meisten sind schwach und mangelernährt. Parasiten und Seuchen setzen den Wiederkäuern zu. Innovative Futterblöcke könnten die Situation verbessern.

programme.title: Albanien
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Über viele Jahrhunderte wanderten albanische Hirten mit ihren Tieren über den ganzen Balkan. Diese Tradition fand ein Ende mit der sozialistischen Diktatur. Nach deren Niedergang besannen sich viele der einstigen Schäfer auf ihre alten Bräuche und versuchten auch ihre Kinder für den Hirtenberuf zu begeistern. Haben die Schäfer eine Zukunft?

programme.title: Norwegen, die Rentierprinzessin
programme.desc: Seit Jahrhunderten treten die Sami mit ihren Rentieren in Rennen gegeneinander an: Gezogen von kräftigen Junghirschen rasen die "Rentierprinzessin" Anne Risten Sara und die weiteren Athleten auf Skiern über einen Rundkurs.

programme.title: Die Herren des Lavendels
programme.desc: Frankreichs berühmte Lavendel-Felder. Jahr für Jahr strömen Besucher hierher, angezogen von diesem besonderen Licht, diesem Blau und Lila. Eine Szenerie wie im Traum. Doch hinter der faszinierenden Kulisse ist längst nicht alles perfekt. Wie steht es in Wahrheit um den französischen Lavendel-Anbau? GEO Reportage war vor Ort.

programme.title: Jemens verschleierte Zukunft
programme.desc: Jemens verschleierte Zukunft? Ein Film von Holger RiedelDer Jemen gilt als eines der schönsten Länder im Vorderen Orient - und gleichzeitig als Land voller Probleme. Krummdolch und Kalaschnikow prägen die Männerwelt und deren Gewaltbereitschaft. Waffen, die Droge Khat und knappe Wasserressourcen sind die Hauptgeschäftsquellen auf dem Land und Anlass für blutige Rivalitäten zwischen den Stämmen. Die Zentralregierung hat jenseits der Hauptstadt Sanaa nichts zu melden - auch nicht gegen die vielerorts praktizierte, Blutrache. Das Frauenbild ist mittelalterlich, und jedes Ansinnen von weiblicher Selbstbestimmung wird im Keim erstickt. In der Atmosphäre von Armut, Gewalt und Korruption versucht ein Mann zwischen den Clans, Stämmen und Geschlechtern zu vermitteln. Planet Weltweit ist es gelungen, einen Blick hinter die Fassaden aus tausendundeiner Nacht zu werfen.

programme.title: Mit der Lok durch Angola
programme.desc: Mit der Lok durch Angola Ein Film von Adama UlrichAngola, Land im Umbruch. Gebeutelt durch den jahrzehntelangen Bürgerkrieg, erlebt der afrikanische Staat am Atlantischen Ozean heute einen Wirtschaftsboom - allerdings nur für ausgewählte Kreise: Während in der Hauptstadt Luanda durch massive Ölförderung die Preise in exorbitante Höhen steigen und eine wirtschaftliche Entwicklung nie gekannten Ausmaßes ankurbeln, bleiben die ländlichen Regionen isoliert. Doch das soll nun anders werden: Mit dem Wiederaufbau der alten Benguela-Bahnlinie, so hoffen die Menschen jenseits der Hauptstadt, sollen auch sie vom Handel profitieren und ein besseres Leben bekommen. Die Dokumentation hat den Mechaniker Joaquim Mohebe und seine instandgesetzte Dampflok auf ihrem Weg durch Angola begleitet.

programme.title: Mike Stern
programme.sub-title: Mike Stern & Didier Lockwood: Jazz à Vienne
programme.desc: Guitarist Mike Stern and violin player Didier Lockwood sharing a stage: that promises a good show! After playing for years with Blood, Sweat & Tears, Mike Stern landed a gig with drummer Billy Cobham and then broke through with Miles Davis' comeback band in the 1980s. Didier Lockwood played in jazz fusion band Magma during the 1970s and is known for his use of electric amplification and experimentation. Together they perform a unique duo concert at the beautiful antique theatre in Vienne, France.

programme.title: Astrud Gilberto & Dizzy Gillespie
programme.sub-title: Gilberto, Gillespie & Skymasters - North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. In 1982, Dutch big band The Skymasters accompanied monumental jazz trumpet legend Dizzy Gillespie and the Brazilian bossa nova singer Astrud Gilberto at the North Sea Jazz Festival in The Hague.

programme.title: Charles Mingus, Jaki Byard, Dannie Richmond & Johnny Coles
programme.sub-title: Charles Mingus And Eric Dolphy live in Liège
programme.desc: Charles Mingus showcases an exceptional concert performed in April 1965 featuring his most celebrated lineup: Jaki Byard (piano), Dannie Richmond (drums), Johnny Coles (trumpet), Clifford Jordan (tenor sax) and the great Eric Dolphy (alto sax, flute and bass clarinet). Recorded within an eight-day span, less than three months before Dolphy's death, the three concerts showcase Mingus's visionary leadership and the band's incredible depth and diversity with unique performances and arrangements of classics including ‘So Long Eric' and the groundbreaking ‘Meditations On Integration'.

programme.title: Miles Davis
programme.desc: American trumpeter Miles Davis (1926-1991) was a pioneering jazz musician from the late 1940s to the late 1980s. His influence on 20th century music is hard to overstate, as he trailblazed bebop, cool jazz, hardbop, modal jazz, and electronic music. On October 11, 1964, Miles Davis performed at Teatro Dell'Arte in Milan. With tenor saxophonist Wayne Shorter, pianist Herbie Hancock, bassist Ron Carter and drummer Tony Williams, Davis performed Autumn Leaves, My Funny Valentine, All Blues, All of You, and Joshua.

programme.title: Philip Catherine, Jean-Louis Rassinfosse & Chet Baker
programme.sub-title: Jazz a la Grand Place Chet Baker Trio
programme.desc: Two top-tier Belgian musicians – guitarist Philip Catherine and bassist Jean-Louis Rassinfosse – accompany American jazz trumpeter and vocalist Chet Baker during this 1985 performance at the beautiful Brussels Jazz Club, located on the Grand-Place, the Belgian capital's central square. The trio plays Charlie Mariano's “Crystal Bells”, the title track of their acclaimed 1983 album. Other songs played during this legendary concert include “Down” and “How Deep is the Ocean”.

programme.title: John Coltrane
programme.sub-title: I want to talk about you
programme.desc: Explore the music of one of the most influential and innovative saxophonists in jazz history: John Coltrane! Immerse yourself in this collection of remarkable performances from the early 1960s that showcase Coltrane's unparalleled artistry and unique sound during a transformative period in the artist's career. Recorded in various European cities, Coltrane is seen playing the songs “Autumn Leaves”, “Hackensack”, “My Favorite Things”, “I Want To Talk About You”, “Vigil”, and “Naima”. Tune in and experience why the music of John Coltrane has touched the lives of so many!

programme.title: Thelonious Monk
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: John Coltrane, McCoy Tyner, Elvin Jones & Jimmy Garrison
programme.desc: The mere mention of the name John Coltrane evokes a deeply emotional, often spiritual response from even the most casual jazz fan. Dexter Gordon was a fantastic saxophonist. Miles Davis was a genius. Coltrane stood above - he was a visionary, a saint-like figure. By the standards of most jazz musicians, his life was uneventful. Sure, he had a heroin habit for a while, and Miles Davis punched him, but once he'd experienced the “spiritual awakening” described in the liner notes of his 1965 album A Love Supreme, he dedicated himself to his music with extreme single-mindedness. This broadcast of Coltrane's 1965 performance at the short-lived Belgian jazz festival in Comblain-la-Tour features Trane's classic quartet with Elvin Jones (drums), Jimmy Garrison (bass) and McCoy Tyner (piano).

programme.title: Christian Scott
programme.sub-title: Christian Scott aTunde Adjuah, West Of The West
programme.desc: In 2019, the vibrant city of Sofia, Bulgaria, hosted the International A to JazZ Festival. Among the featured acts was the trailblazing jazz trumpeter Christian Scott aTunde Adjuah. This genre-defying artist captivated the audience with his eclectic “stretch music” an approach that incorporates hip-hop and reaches back through the American canon into African percussion and its rich melodic content. Trumpeter Christian Scott aTunde Adjuah's quintet, which includes drummer Corey Fonville, percussionist Weedie Braimah, pianist Lawrence Fields, and bass guitarist Max Mucha, delivered a performance that defied boundaries and expectations.

programme.title: Soft Rock
programme.desc: During the 1960s rock n roll splintered into a rainbow of genres – musicians were experimenting. Soft rock began as a blend of the progressive rock quest for musicianship and the songwriter's love of pop. It originated in the late 1960s in Southern California and the United Kingdom. The style relied on simple, melodic songs with big, lush productions. This new genre established bands such as Supertramp, ELO & Barclay James Harvest

programme.title: Philippe Jordan, Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris, Choeur de l'Opéra national de Paris & Ricarda Merbeth
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125
programme.desc: Swiss conductor Philippe Jordan and the Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris recorded all of Ludwig van Beethoven's symphonies in 2014-2015. In this program, maestro Jordan presents Beethoven's final symphony: Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125. He conducts the Orchestre and Choeurs de l'Opéra national de Paris and four vocal soloists Ricarda Merbeth (soprano), Daniela Sindram (mezzosoprano), Robert Dean Smith (tenor), and Günther Groissböck (bass). Beethoven composed his last Symphony when his hearing had all but gone, between 1822 and 1824. Symphony No. 9 is the longest and most ambitious of Beethoven's symphonies. Most striking is the piece's finale movement, which includes a choir and four vocal soloists singing a setting of Friedrich Schiller's poem ‘An die Freude' (Ode to Joy). This performance was recorded at Opéra Bastille in Paris, France, in 2015.

programme.title: Chen Xue-Hong, Zhang Cheng, Chen Yunjie & Chen Sa
programme.sub-title: Piano works by Chopin, Scriabin, Schumann & Liszt
programme.desc: In recent years, a new generation of Chinese pianists has emerged on the international scene. But there are many more young Chinese artists, who the Académie France-Chine aims to enable to deepen their art by introducing them to and giving them a platform within French and European culture. Four of these artists are Chen Xue-Hong, Zhang Cheng, Chen Yunjie and Chen Sa, who made their joint debut in Paris in this unique concert at the Théâtre des Champs-Élysées that showcased their extraordinary talent. On the program are Chopin's Piano Sonata No. 2, Schumann's Piano Sonata No. 1, Scriabin's Piano Sonata No. 8 and Paysage (No. 3) and Mazeppa (No. 4) from Liszt's Études d'Exécution Transcendante. The concert closes with Messiaen's Regard de l'Esprit de la joie (No. 10) from Vingt regards sur l'Enfant-Jésus.

programme.title: Neeme Järvi, Lucerne Symphony Orchestra, Martha Argerich & Mischa Maisky
programme.sub-title: Shchedrin's Double Concerto, Franck and Dvorák
programme.desc: The Lucerne Symphony Orchestra under the baton of Neeme Järvi presents the world premiere of Rodion Shchedrin's Double concerto for cello, piano and orchestra. Soloists are Martha Argerich (piano) and Mischa Maisky (cello). The concert program features Antonín Dvořák's Scherzo capriccioso Des-Dur Op. 66, B 131, Shchedrin's aforementioned Double concerto "Romantic Offering", César Franck's Sonata for piano and cello in A, and Dmitri Shostakovich's Symphony No. 9, Op. 70. This première performance was recorded at the Culture and Congress Centre of Lucerne, KKL, on February 9, 2011. The Lucerne Symphony Orchestra is orchestra-in-residence at KKL Luzern. The Lucerne Symphony Orchestra is Switzerland's oldest symphony orchestra and has won an international standing that extends far beyond its home base.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika

programme.title: Kinderstube Wildnis Bei den Affen
programme.desc: Die Tonka-Makaken bevölkern die Tempel auf Sri Lanka. In einem der Clans erblickt das kleine Affen-Mädchen Gremlin das Licht der Welt. Von Geburt an muss es sich in dem lauten Gewusel aus Familienbanden und Fehden mit benachbarten Truppen behaupten. Das Gruppenleben ist von einer strengen Hierarchie bestimmt. Die Machtkämpfe zwischen und innerhalb der Familienverbände bergen ebenso viele Gefahren wie lauernde Greifvögel und die angrenzende Straße. Allzu oft geraten die noch wehrlosen Babys zwischen die Fronten. Bei Übergriffen durch Ranghöhere müssen Mütter oft zusehen, wie unsanft mit ihrem Nachwuchs umgegangen wird. Nur jedes dritte Makaken-Kind kann sich durchsetzen und überlebt seine ersten Monate. Der niedrige Rang der Mutter und obendrein ihre auffällige weiße Schwanzspitze sind nicht die besten Voraussetzungen für die kleine Gremlin. Doch das aufgeweckte Äffchen lernt schnell dazu und entpuppt sich als wahre Kämpfernatur.

programme.title: Wunder der Wissenschaft Rettendes Gift und brennende Hosen

programme.title: Marokkos weißes Gold
programme.desc: Die Arganie, ein dornenbewehrter Baum, wächst nur im Südwesten Marokkos. Seine Früchte liefern das begehrte Arganöl, welches von den Frauen der Region seit Jahrhunderten in mühevoller Handarbeit produziert wird. Inzwischen kommen auch Europäer auf den Geschmack dieser einzigartigen Kostbarkeit. Und nicht nur das: Neben seinen kulinarischen Qualitäten lässt sich das Öl ebenso gut als Kosmetikprodukt und Heilmittel vermarkten. Planet Weltweit hat den Frauen Marokkos bei der aufwändigen Ölherstellung über die Schulter geschaut und beobachtet, wie sie sie versuchen, ihr traditionelles Kleinod für den internationalen Wettbewerb vorzubereiten.Sechs Uhr morgens in einem kleinen Dorf im Südwesten Marokkos. Die Männer sind bereits zur Arbeit aufgebrochen. Auch Arbia el Kasri verlässt das Haus, um ihrem Beruf nachzugehen. Vor fünf Jahren noch war es für eine Frau unvorstellbar außerhalb des Hauses Arbeit zu finden. In dieser Region Marokkos verlassen die Bäuerinnen eigentlich nie ihre Douar, ihre kleinen Dörfer. Doch nun sind es einige Hunderte, die sich wie Arbia täglich in kleinen Kooperativen einfinden, welche die Frauen selbst gegründet haben. Hier produzieren sie Arganöl - eine Kunst, die Marokkanerinnen bereits seit Jahrhunderten beherrschen. Das Öl ist überaus nährstoffre ...

programme.title: Der Weinpriester von Bali
programme.desc: Bali - Tropenparadies und Insel der Götter. Dem 42-jährigen Hindu Rai Budarsa gelang es als Erstem, Wein auf Bali zu kultivieren. Dreimal im Jahr kann auf der tropischen Insel geerntet werden. Für den Unternehmer ein Segen - doch für den gläubigen Hindu in Anbetracht der vielen religiösen Feste und Zeremonien eine Herausforderung. Ob Rai Budarsa der Balanceakt zwischen dem harten Alltag eines Unternehmers und seinen religiösen Verpflichtungen gelingt, davon erzählt diese Episode von Planet Weltweit.Bereits seit einer Stunde wartet die Prozession für die Leichenbestattung auf der Straße. Rai Budarsa streift eilig sein Poloshirt und die Bermudas ab, denn als höchster Vertreter einer Priesterkaste muss er jede Zeremonie in seiner Gemeinde leiten. Als sein Blackberry klingelt, schafft er es gerade noch den Knoten seines schwarzen Sarongs festzuziehen, bevor er den Anruf entgegennimmt. Es ist sein Kellermeister, der Australier Don Buchanan: Ihm fehlen Flaschen für die Abfüllung des Pino de Bali, dem Spitzenprodukt seines Unternehmens Hatten Wines. Der Container mit den Flaschen hängt irgendwo fest - ausgerechnet jetzt, wo während der religiösen Feiertage auf Bali die Restaurants und Hotels mit dem regionalen Wein beliefert werden müssen. Im Laufschritt verspricht Rai Budar ...

programme.title: Die Köchin von Bahia
programme.desc: Die afro-brasilianische Kultur ist nirgendwo so lebendig wie in Salvador de Bahia und in der Religion Candombl?. Die Köchin Elaine Cruz lebt und kocht nach den Regeln dieser Religion und zaubert einzigartige Spezialitäten, die Götter und Menschen gleichermaßen munden. Planet Weltweit hat Elaine beim Kochen für ein großes Fest einer Candombl?-Gemeinde über die Schulter geschaut.

programme.title: Freiheit auf Pferderücken
programme.sub-title: Der lange Weg der Nez Perce
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: 1877 weigerten sich rund 750 Angehörige des Stammes der Nez Perce, im Nordwesten der USA, ihre Freiheit aufzugeben und sich in ein Reservat zu begeben. Stattdessen begaben sie sich mit 2.000 Pferden, überwiegend Appaloosas, auf eine abenteuerliche und verlustreiche Flucht über gut 2.000 km quer durch die Rocky Mountains.

programme.title: Laos
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Wasserbüffel gelten in Laos als "Sparbücher für Notzeiten". Muss jemand ins Krankenhaus, geht der Reis aus oder steht eine Hochzeit an, verkauft man einen Büffel. Doch die meisten sind schwach und mangelernährt. Parasiten und Seuchen setzen den Wiederkäuern zu. Innovative Futterblöcke könnten die Situation verbessern.

programme.title: Albanien
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Über viele Jahrhunderte wanderten albanische Hirten mit ihren Tieren über den ganzen Balkan. Diese Tradition fand ein Ende mit der sozialistischen Diktatur. Nach deren Niedergang besannen sich viele der einstigen Schäfer auf ihre alten Bräuche und versuchten auch ihre Kinder für den Hirtenberuf zu begeistern. Haben die Schäfer eine Zukunft?

programme.title: Norwegen, die Rentierprinzessin
programme.desc: Seit Jahrhunderten treten die Sami mit ihren Rentieren in Rennen gegeneinander an: Gezogen von kräftigen Junghirschen rasen die "Rentierprinzessin" Anne Risten Sara und die weiteren Athleten auf Skiern über einen Rundkurs.

programme.title: Die Herren des Lavendels
programme.desc: Frankreichs berühmte Lavendel-Felder. Jahr für Jahr strömen Besucher hierher, angezogen von diesem besonderen Licht, diesem Blau und Lila. Eine Szenerie wie im Traum. Doch hinter der faszinierenden Kulisse ist längst nicht alles perfekt. Wie steht es in Wahrheit um den französischen Lavendel-Anbau? GEO Reportage war vor Ort.

programme.title: Jemens verschleierte Zukunft
programme.desc: Jemens verschleierte Zukunft? Ein Film von Holger RiedelDer Jemen gilt als eines der schönsten Länder im Vorderen Orient - und gleichzeitig als Land voller Probleme. Krummdolch und Kalaschnikow prägen die Männerwelt und deren Gewaltbereitschaft. Waffen, die Droge Khat und knappe Wasserressourcen sind die Hauptgeschäftsquellen auf dem Land und Anlass für blutige Rivalitäten zwischen den Stämmen. Die Zentralregierung hat jenseits der Hauptstadt Sanaa nichts zu melden - auch nicht gegen die vielerorts praktizierte, Blutrache. Das Frauenbild ist mittelalterlich, und jedes Ansinnen von weiblicher Selbstbestimmung wird im Keim erstickt. In der Atmosphäre von Armut, Gewalt und Korruption versucht ein Mann zwischen den Clans, Stämmen und Geschlechtern zu vermitteln. Planet Weltweit ist es gelungen, einen Blick hinter die Fassaden aus tausendundeiner Nacht zu werfen.

programme.title: Mit der Lok durch Angola
programme.desc: Mit der Lok durch Angola Ein Film von Adama UlrichAngola, Land im Umbruch. Gebeutelt durch den jahrzehntelangen Bürgerkrieg, erlebt der afrikanische Staat am Atlantischen Ozean heute einen Wirtschaftsboom - allerdings nur für ausgewählte Kreise: Während in der Hauptstadt Luanda durch massive Ölförderung die Preise in exorbitante Höhen steigen und eine wirtschaftliche Entwicklung nie gekannten Ausmaßes ankurbeln, bleiben die ländlichen Regionen isoliert. Doch das soll nun anders werden: Mit dem Wiederaufbau der alten Benguela-Bahnlinie, so hoffen die Menschen jenseits der Hauptstadt, sollen auch sie vom Handel profitieren und ein besseres Leben bekommen. Die Dokumentation hat den Mechaniker Joaquim Mohebe und seine instandgesetzte Dampflok auf ihrem Weg durch Angola begleitet.

programme.title: Gaudí, Picasso y el Hospital Más Antiguo del Mundo
programme.desc: La historia del Hospital de la Santa Creu i Sant Pau, el más antiguo del mundo, construido en el año 1401 en la capital catalana. Fue admirado por artistas como Picasso y el arquitecto Gaudí, que pidió pasar sus últimos días allí. El hospital murió y renació de sus cenizas: hoy en día es una joya arquitectónica, un hospital concebido como una ciudad jardín declarada Patrimonio de la Humanidad por la UNESCO en 1985. Seis siglos después de la colocación de la primera piedra, el hospital se encuentra en pleno funcionamiento y ya se está trabajando para la construcción de un nuevo edificio.

programme.title: [마음이 차분해지는 정원] 담양 소쇄원
programme.desc: 담양 소쇄원은 양산보(梁山甫: 1503~1557)가 스승인 조광조가 유배되자 세상의 뜻을 버리고 고향으로 내려와 깨끗하고 시원하다는 의미를 담아 조성한 정원입니다. 이 아름다운 정원은 조선시대를 대표하는 정원으로, 우리나라 선비의 고고한 품성과 절의를 엿볼 수 있습니다. ※ 담양 소쇄원 (사적 제 304호, 명승 제 40호)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [창덕궁 봄꽃 개화 현장] 낙선재 뒷뜰, 돌배나무 풍경
programme.desc: 창덕궁은 태종 때 건립된 조선왕조의 왕궁으로, 처음에는 경복궁의 이궁으로 지어졌지만 경복궁보다 더욱 오래 법궁의 역할을 해왔습니다. 특히 창덕궁 후원은 한국의 유일한 궁궐후원이라는 점에서 그 가치가 매우 높지요. 한국의 대표적인 정원인 창덕궁이 봄을 맞이하는 아름다운 모습을 감상해보세요! ※ 창덕궁 (사적 제122호, 1997년 유네스코 세계문화유산)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [오늘도 평화로운 갯벌] 해질녘의 광활한 갯벌, 순천만
programme.desc: 순천만은 남해안 중서부에 위치한 만으로, 갯벌에 펼쳐지는 갈대밭과 칠면초 군락 등이 어우러져 아름다운 해안 생태경관을 보입니다. 넓은 갯벌에는 다양한 갯벌 생물들이 살고, 천연기념물인 흑두루미를 비롯한 국제 희귀 조류가 찾는 순천만의 풍경을 감상해 보세요! ※ 전라남도 순천시 순천만 (명승 제41호) / 한국의 갯벌 (2021년 유네스코 세계자연유산)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [오늘도 평화로운 갯벌] 바람에 흔들리는 갈대숲, 순천만
programme.desc: 순천만은 남해안 중서부에 위치한 만으로, 갯벌에 펼쳐지는 갈대밭과 칠면초 군락 등이 어우러져 아름다운 해안 생태경관을 보입니다. 넓은 갯벌에는 다양한 갯벌 생물들이 살고, 천연기념물인 흑두루미를 비롯한 국제 희귀 조류가 찾는 순천만의 풍경을 감상해 보세요! ※ 전라남도 순천시 순천만 (명승 제41호) / 한국의 갯벌 (2021년 유네스코 세계자연유산)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [조선왕릉 가을 숲길] 숲길로 이어진 어머니와 아들, 태릉과 강릉
programme.desc: 서울의 태릉은 조선 제11대 왕 중종의 제2계비인 문정왕후가, 강릉은 조선 제13대 왕 명종과 명종비 인순왕후가 잠들어있는 곳입니다. 두 능은 연결되어있어 태릉에서 호젓한 숲길을 따라 30분 정도 걸으면 강릉까지 한번에 만날 수 있답니다. ※ 서울 태릉과 강릉 (사적 제201호) / 조선왕릉 (2009년 유네스코 세계문화유산)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 사방탁자를 만들다. 소목장
programme.desc: 소목장은 건물의 창호, 목기, 목가구를 제작하는 목수를 말합니다. 이들은 전통 목공예기법으로 무늬가 있는 나무를 사용하여 자연스러운 미를 살려냅니다. 검소한 조선시대 문방생활을 운치있게 만들어주던 사방탁자를 만드는 과정을 감상해 보세요. (박명배 / 국가무형문화재 소목장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 작품이 되기 위한 인고의 시간. 바닥파기
programme.desc: 벼루는 물을 붓고 먹을 가는 돌을 말합니다. 단양 자석벼루는 붉은색을 띄는 원석으로 만들어집니다. 자석벼루장인이 벼루를 만들어내기 위해 바닥을 파내는 과정을 영상으로 담았습니다. 장인의 집요하고 끈기있는 벼루 제작과정을 ASMR영상을 통하여 함께 만나보시죠. (신재민 / 충북무형문화재 자석벼루장 전승교육사)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 전통을 지키는 인내. 옹기장
programme.desc: 한국인의 집집마다 적게는 네다섯 개부터 많게는 수십 개씩 가지고 있던 옹기는 한국 도자기 역사상 가장 오랜 전통을 지니고 있으며 널리 쓰이던 생활용기입니다. 옹기장 보유자가 만들어 내는 옹기의 전 제작과정을 지켜보고, 전통을 꿋꿋이 지키며 빚어온 옹기에 쏟는 정성과 인내를 배워봅시다. (정윤석, 정영균 / 국가무형문화재 옹기장 보유자, 이수자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 시간이 만들어내는 명작. 먹(Meok)
programme.desc: 먹은 예로부터 선비의 친구 문방사우(먹, 종이, 붓, 벼루) 중 하나로 우리의 뛰어난 기록문화유산들을 만드는 중요한 소재였습니다. 소나무를 태워 만든 연기 속에서 얻은 그을음에 아교를 넣어 먹 반죽을 만들고, 형틀에 넣어 먹을 제조하는 송연먹을 제작하는 과정을 함께 감상해봅시다. (한상묵 / 전통 먹장 숙련기술자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: Mike Stern
programme.sub-title: Mike Stern & Didier Lockwood: Jazz à Vienne
programme.desc: Guitarist Mike Stern and violin player Didier Lockwood sharing a stage: that promises a good show! After playing for years with Blood, Sweat & Tears, Mike Stern landed a gig with drummer Billy Cobham and then broke through with Miles Davis' comeback band in the 1980s. Didier Lockwood played in jazz fusion band Magma during the 1970s and is known for his use of electric amplification and experimentation. Together they perform a unique duo concert at the beautiful antique theatre in Vienne, France.

programme.title: Astrud Gilberto & Dizzy Gillespie
programme.sub-title: Gilberto, Gillespie & Skymasters - North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. In 1982, Dutch big band The Skymasters accompanied monumental jazz trumpet legend Dizzy Gillespie and the Brazilian bossa nova singer Astrud Gilberto at the North Sea Jazz Festival in The Hague.

programme.title: Charles Mingus, Jaki Byard, Dannie Richmond & Johnny Coles
programme.sub-title: Charles Mingus And Eric Dolphy live in Liège
programme.desc: Charles Mingus showcases an exceptional concert performed in April 1965 featuring his most celebrated lineup: Jaki Byard (piano), Dannie Richmond (drums), Johnny Coles (trumpet), Clifford Jordan (tenor sax) and the great Eric Dolphy (alto sax, flute and bass clarinet). Recorded within an eight-day span, less than three months before Dolphy's death, the three concerts showcase Mingus's visionary leadership and the band's incredible depth and diversity with unique performances and arrangements of classics including ‘So Long Eric' and the groundbreaking ‘Meditations On Integration'.

programme.title: Miles Davis
programme.desc: American trumpeter Miles Davis (1926-1991) was a pioneering jazz musician from the late 1940s to the late 1980s. His influence on 20th century music is hard to overstate, as he trailblazed bebop, cool jazz, hardbop, modal jazz, and electronic music. On October 11, 1964, Miles Davis performed at Teatro Dell'Arte in Milan. With tenor saxophonist Wayne Shorter, pianist Herbie Hancock, bassist Ron Carter and drummer Tony Williams, Davis performed Autumn Leaves, My Funny Valentine, All Blues, All of You, and Joshua.

programme.title: Philip Catherine, Jean-Louis Rassinfosse & Chet Baker
programme.sub-title: Jazz a la Grand Place Chet Baker Trio
programme.desc: Two top-tier Belgian musicians – guitarist Philip Catherine and bassist Jean-Louis Rassinfosse – accompany American jazz trumpeter and vocalist Chet Baker during this 1985 performance at the beautiful Brussels Jazz Club, located on the Grand-Place, the Belgian capital's central square. The trio plays Charlie Mariano's “Crystal Bells”, the title track of their acclaimed 1983 album. Other songs played during this legendary concert include “Down” and “How Deep is the Ocean”.

programme.title: John Coltrane
programme.sub-title: I want to talk about you
programme.desc: Explore the music of one of the most influential and innovative saxophonists in jazz history: John Coltrane! Immerse yourself in this collection of remarkable performances from the early 1960s that showcase Coltrane's unparalleled artistry and unique sound during a transformative period in the artist's career. Recorded in various European cities, Coltrane is seen playing the songs “Autumn Leaves”, “Hackensack”, “My Favorite Things”, “I Want To Talk About You”, “Vigil”, and “Naima”. Tune in and experience why the music of John Coltrane has touched the lives of so many!

programme.title: Thelonious Monk
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: John Coltrane, McCoy Tyner, Elvin Jones & Jimmy Garrison
programme.desc: The mere mention of the name John Coltrane evokes a deeply emotional, often spiritual response from even the most casual jazz fan. Dexter Gordon was a fantastic saxophonist. Miles Davis was a genius. Coltrane stood above - he was a visionary, a saint-like figure. By the standards of most jazz musicians, his life was uneventful. Sure, he had a heroin habit for a while, and Miles Davis punched him, but once he'd experienced the “spiritual awakening” described in the liner notes of his 1965 album A Love Supreme, he dedicated himself to his music with extreme single-mindedness. This broadcast of Coltrane's 1965 performance at the short-lived Belgian jazz festival in Comblain-la-Tour features Trane's classic quartet with Elvin Jones (drums), Jimmy Garrison (bass) and McCoy Tyner (piano).

programme.title: Christian Scott
programme.sub-title: Christian Scott aTunde Adjuah, West Of The West
programme.desc: In 2019, the vibrant city of Sofia, Bulgaria, hosted the International A to JazZ Festival. Among the featured acts was the trailblazing jazz trumpeter Christian Scott aTunde Adjuah. This genre-defying artist captivated the audience with his eclectic “stretch music” an approach that incorporates hip-hop and reaches back through the American canon into African percussion and its rich melodic content. Trumpeter Christian Scott aTunde Adjuah's quintet, which includes drummer Corey Fonville, percussionist Weedie Braimah, pianist Lawrence Fields, and bass guitarist Max Mucha, delivered a performance that defied boundaries and expectations.

programme.title: Soft Rock
programme.desc: During the 1960s rock n roll splintered into a rainbow of genres – musicians were experimenting. Soft rock began as a blend of the progressive rock quest for musicianship and the songwriter's love of pop. It originated in the late 1960s in Southern California and the United Kingdom. The style relied on simple, melodic songs with big, lush productions. This new genre established bands such as Supertramp, ELO & Barclay James Harvest

programme.title: Philippe Jordan, Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris, Choeur de l'Opéra national de Paris & Ricarda Merbeth
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125
programme.desc: Swiss conductor Philippe Jordan and the Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris recorded all of Ludwig van Beethoven's symphonies in 2014-2015. In this program, maestro Jordan presents Beethoven's final symphony: Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125. He conducts the Orchestre and Choeurs de l'Opéra national de Paris and four vocal soloists Ricarda Merbeth (soprano), Daniela Sindram (mezzosoprano), Robert Dean Smith (tenor), and Günther Groissböck (bass). Beethoven composed his last Symphony when his hearing had all but gone, between 1822 and 1824. Symphony No. 9 is the longest and most ambitious of Beethoven's symphonies. Most striking is the piece's finale movement, which includes a choir and four vocal soloists singing a setting of Friedrich Schiller's poem ‘An die Freude' (Ode to Joy). This performance was recorded at Opéra Bastille in Paris, France, in 2015.

programme.title: Chen Xue-Hong, Zhang Cheng, Chen Yunjie & Chen Sa
programme.sub-title: Piano works by Chopin, Scriabin, Schumann & Liszt
programme.desc: In recent years, a new generation of Chinese pianists has emerged on the international scene. But there are many more young Chinese artists, who the Académie France-Chine aims to enable to deepen their art by introducing them to and giving them a platform within French and European culture. Four of these artists are Chen Xue-Hong, Zhang Cheng, Chen Yunjie and Chen Sa, who made their joint debut in Paris in this unique concert at the Théâtre des Champs-Élysées that showcased their extraordinary talent. On the program are Chopin's Piano Sonata No. 2, Schumann's Piano Sonata No. 1, Scriabin's Piano Sonata No. 8 and Paysage (No. 3) and Mazeppa (No. 4) from Liszt's Études d'Exécution Transcendante. The concert closes with Messiaen's Regard de l'Esprit de la joie (No. 10) from Vingt regards sur l'Enfant-Jésus.

programme.title: Neeme Järvi, Lucerne Symphony Orchestra, Martha Argerich & Mischa Maisky
programme.sub-title: Shchedrin's Double Concerto, Franck and Dvorák
programme.desc: The Lucerne Symphony Orchestra under the baton of Neeme Järvi presents the world premiere of Rodion Shchedrin's Double concerto for cello, piano and orchestra. Soloists are Martha Argerich (piano) and Mischa Maisky (cello). The concert program features Antonín Dvořák's Scherzo capriccioso Des-Dur Op. 66, B 131, Shchedrin's aforementioned Double concerto "Romantic Offering", César Franck's Sonata for piano and cello in A, and Dmitri Shostakovich's Symphony No. 9, Op. 70. This première performance was recorded at the Culture and Congress Centre of Lucerne, KKL, on February 9, 2011. The Lucerne Symphony Orchestra is orchestra-in-residence at KKL Luzern. The Lucerne Symphony Orchestra is Switzerland's oldest symphony orchestra and has won an international standing that extends far beyond its home base.

Special thanks to Elliot & Des Manning for filming & editing as well as music by Christopher Lloyd Clarke of EnlightenedAudio.com. Filmed at South Australia's Cape Jervis, overlooking Saint Vincent Gulf - and Woakwine Range.

programme.title: Rainbow Reef Relaxation II 2
programme.desc: Immerse your senses on an unparalleled underwater journey to some of the world's most vibrant coral reefs and undersea paradises as seen in true 4K Ultra High Definition, paired to soothing new music by Relax Moods. Viewers will discover a plethora of stunning sea creatures, thanks to the incredible underwater cinematography by Peter Schneider filmed over the last several years.

programme.title: A Day in Paradise 3
programme.desc: A graciously flowing four hour long pure nature relaxation experience, "A Day In Paradise" immerses viewers in the sights and sounds of one of the world's most pure and picturesque tropical islands - for an entire day from sunrise, to sunset. Filmed in 2013 by David Huting, the tiny island is hidden off of the northeastern coast of the outer Fiji Islands (near Taveuni), and boasts a perfect white sandy beach, groves of palm trees, and a majestic lagoon that shelters the island from all sides. It has more turtle visitors than humans!

programme.title: Glistening Island Beach
programme.desc: An instant classic and perfect scene for mental escape, "Glistening Island Beach" places viewers underneath a big beautiful palm tree facing a perfect white sandy beach, glistening blue sea, sunshine, and the small boat you arrived in. Filmed in 4K Ultra High Definition on the hidden [and now privately owned] exotic island of Nanuku, where a small atoll is surrounded by an untouched perfect lagoon, miles away from it all....

programme.title: New Year Cheer II
programme.desc: New Year Cheer E2 — Step into a world of dynamic artistry in the spirit of the new year with festive portrayals of hope, renewal, and optimism. The music is celebratory, featuring are electro and soft house with funk rhythms held by bass lines and energetic drums.

programme.title: New Year Cheer: Lunar New Year
programme.desc: New Year Cheer: Lunar New Year E4 — Celebrating tradition and prosperity, this collections showcases the vibrant colors, mythical creatures, and auspicious symbols that define this joyous occasion. Usher in the lunar new year with ethereal music that connects East and West.

programme.title: Diverse Perspectives: Black Artists Now III
programme.desc: Black Artists Now E3 — A transcendent journey celebrating the vibrancy & diversity of black culture. From evocative photographs to vivid canvases, this collection pays homage to the global tapestry of black identity, uniting voices and visions that resonate with the soul.
